<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-097-123 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 026 006</DOCID><JOURNAL>Publish!andP;  August 1991 v6 n8 p120(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Electronic paper: fulfilling the promise.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Warnock, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A central concept to achieving some portion of the paperlessoffice ideal is an 'electronic paper' technology that enables theelectronic transfer of any kind of document (including multiplefonts, embedded graphics and photographs) across any computerenvironment and any distance.andP;  Sixty percent of the time ofbusiness professionals involves document handling.andP;  Currenttechnologies, though, do not easily support transfer of complexdocuments electronically.andP;  What is required to achieve viableelectronic paper technology are a totally device-independentformat for self-contained documents and a program that can displayor print the document on any system.andP;  PostScript-language filesinclude most of the required characteristics of electronic paper,but software drivers are required to add font outline informationinto the document and support viewing and printing processes.andO;Such hardware technologies as high-speed font-rasterizing chipswill facilitate the implementation of electronic paper.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Document Management SystemsElectronic Mail SystemsRequirements AnalysisFuture Technologies.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>